<div id="review_1893625649" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1893625649" />
    <a title="Nikos79" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5111810-nikos79"><img alt="Nikos79" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1472295901p2/5111810.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1893625649?book_show_action=true">Jun 08, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nikos79" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nikos79" href="/user/show/5111810-nikos79">Nikos79</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1893625649" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9964787883577426289">Before saying anything else, I have to confess that I &apos;m very big fan of mafia stuff, when it comes to movies, tv series, documentaries, books etc. I find the topic extremely interesting and intriguing, and almost all times leaves me a great taste and sense of satisfaction. Having said this, it&apos;s not a surprise that I loved this book (as well).<br/><br/>Some years ago before reading the Godfather, Puzo&apos;s most famous book, I had many doubts about how good could it be, since the movie trilogy is simply extr</span>
  <span id="freeText9964787883577426289" style="display:none">Before saying anything else, I have to confess that I 'm very big fan of mafia stuff, when it comes to movies, tv series, documentaries, books etc. I find the topic extremely interesting and intriguing, and almost all times leaves me a great taste and sense of satisfaction. Having said this, it's not a surprise that I loved this book (as well).<br /><br />Some years ago before reading the Godfather, Puzo's most famous book, I had many doubts about how good could it be, since the movie trilogy is simply extraordinary, a masterpiece for my taste. When I finished that book I remember myself being fascinated, it was a great reading too. Now, before starting The Sicilian, for one more time I was really cautious, wondering, will it be as good as the Godfather, can it meet my expectations, or it will disappoint me? Hopefully, it turned out to be a superb reading as well.<br /><br />It is not actually a sequel to Godfather, it just shares some common characters. This one takes place in Sicily at 40's and follows the story of Salvatore Guiliano, who became the most famous and the same time beloved thief of Sicily, from his teen years to his rise becoming one of the leading personalities in Italy of that era. As a literature character is absolutely wonderful, his story is a pure joy to read, the background is great and above all his romantic nature over life. Except all vendetas, alliances, betrayals, guns, fights etc someone can see this book as a great folklore approach of Sicily too. I must not forget to add that I found it very very well written. Fantastic reading.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9964787883577426289" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


